revision.text:
'''Bachelor of Arts and Science (B.A.S.''' or '''B.A.&Sc.''' or '''B.A.Sc.)''' is an [[undergraduate]] [[bachelor's degree]] conferred by a small number of [[United States|American]] universities and a fair number of universities in other English-speaking countries (including [[Canada]] and [[Australia]]). Generally, to receive a B.A.S. degree, a student would need to complete the general requirements for a bachelor's degree and also the requirements for two different [[academic major]]s (or [[academic minor]]s) — one that usually leads to a [[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]] degree and one that usually leads to a [[Bachelor of Science|B.S.]] degree. In the United States, the degree is meant to be a four-year degree, but many students will take five years to complete the program.{{Citation needed|date=January 2011}}

Technically speaking, it is not an example of a [[double degree]], as universities only confer a single degree.<ref>[http://registrar.ucdavis.edu/ucdwebcatalog/academicinfo/major.html UC Davis Registrar] {{Webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20120716235722/http://registrar.ucdavis.edu/ucdwebcatalog/academicinfo/major.html |date=2012-07-16 }} ''"A single degree is granted to students who graduate with multiple majors."''</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://registrar.stanford.edu/bulletin/4871.htm |title=Stanford University Registrar |access-date=2011-01-31 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110507022714/http://registrar.stanford.edu/bulletin/4871.htm |archive-date=2011-05-07 |dead-url=yes |df= }}</ref>

