{{Infobox scientist | name = Eugénie Luce | image = Luce Ben Aben School of Arab Embroidery I, Algiers, Algeria.png | image_size = | caption = Luce Ben Aben School, circa 1899 | birth_date = 1804 | birth_place = | death_date = 1882 | death_place = [[Montrichard]], France | residence = | citizenship = | nationality = | ethnicity = | field = Education | work_institution = [[Luce Ben Aben School]] (Luce's school for Muslim girls) in [[Algiers, Algeria]] | alma_mater = | doctoral_advisor = | doctoral_students = | known_for = | author_abbreviation_bot = | author_abbreviation_zoo = | prizes = | religion = | footnotes = }}
'''Eugénie Luce''' (1804-1882) was a French educator, who she founded the first French/Arab school for Muslim girls the [[Luce Ben Aben School]] in [[Algiers]] in 1845.
==Biography==
Eugénie Luce moved to [[Algiers]] in the 1830s, where she became a governess. She left behind her husband and family in France.{{sfn|Rogers|2013|p=}}
===Luce Ben Aben School=== <!-- The Wikipedia article [[Luce Ben Aben School]] redirects here. -->
Eugénie Luce started the Luce Ben Aben School, in 1845.<ref name="Rogers"/> It was the first Franco-Arab school for [[Muslim]] girls,<ref>{{cite journal |last=Rogers |first=Rebecca |date=1 January 2012 |title=A l'école arabe de Mme Luce |trans-title=At the Arab school of Mrs. Luce |url=http://www.histoire.presse.fr/mensuel/371/a-l-ecole-arabe-de-mme-luce-01-01-2012-41664 |language=french |journal=L'Histoire |accessdate=13 December 2013 |issue=371 |page=52}}</ref> dispensing a European-style education. Girls learned French,Arabic, arithmetic, embroidery, geography and sewing. The school was funded by the [[French Algeria]] government until 1861, after which it became a [[trade school]]. They taught [[embroidery]] and other subjects in order to educate the girls in traditional Algerian crafts, at a time when these crafts were being replaced by machine-made imports.<ref name="WDL 8800">{{cite web |url = http://www.wdl.org/en/item/8800/ |title = Luce Ben Aben School of Arab Embroidery I, Algiers, Algeria |website = [[World Digital Library]] |year = 1899 |accessdate = 26 September 2013 }}</ref><ref name="WDL 8803">{{cite web |url = http://www.wdl.org/en/item/8803/ |title = Luce Ben Aben School of Arab Embroidery II, Algiers, Algeria |website = [[World Digital Library]] |year = 1899 }}</ref> These goods were exported throughout Algeria, as well as Europe and the United States.<ref name="Rogers"/>
The school was forced to close on 1 January 1846 because of lack of financial support from the local French government. Eugénie went to Paris to ask for help from the central government, after having managed to get support for school, it was reopened in June 1846. In January 1847 the French government formally agreed to support the school.<ref name="trc-leiden.nl">https://trc-leiden.nl/trc-needles/people-and-functions/authors-scholars-and-activists/madame-eugenie-luce-1804-1882</ref>
In 1858 she had over 120 pupils of different age groups. This school produced skilled embroideresses, who appeared in the London Exhibition of 1862, in the Algerian Pavilion of the 1893 World's Columbian Exhibition at Chicago.<ref name="trc-leiden.nl"/>
The school continued under Madame Luce's daughter and later her granddaughter, Madame Luce Ben-Aben.
===Later life===
Luce would eventually return to [[Montrichard]],<ref name="Rogers">{{cite web|last=Rogers|first=Rebecca E.|title=Promoting the Welfare of Indigenous Women: Franco-Algerian Itineraries (1845-1915)|url=http://scholarworks.umass.edu/berksconference/Workshops/184/1/|work=Workshop Papers|publisher=Berkshrie Conference of Women Historians|accessdate=26 September 2013}}</ref> in France, where she died in 1882. After Luce died, her granddaughter Madame Ben-Aben continued to run the school until her own death in 1915.<ref name="WDL 8800"/><ref>{{cite journal |first=C |last=Conybeare-Grezel |title=La scolarisation des filles musulmanes, une entreprise difficile |trans-title=The scolarization of muslim girls, a difficult enterprise |url=http://www.cerclealgerianiste.asso.fr/contenu/enseignements305.htm |date=14 May 1981 |issue=14 |language=french |journal=L'Algérianiste |accessdate=13 December 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131218110426/http://www.cerclealgerianiste.asso.fr/contenu/enseignements305.htm |archive-date=2013-12-18 |dead-url=yes |df= }}</ref>
